    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-12-28T04:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-12-28T04:30:00-05:00" n="459"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d459">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">656.56D/12–2851: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Indonesia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Cochran</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Djakarta</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-12-28T17:00:00+07:30"
                            >December 28, 1951—5 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>920. <gloss target="#t_FonMin1">FonMin</gloss> Subardjo told me 28th Neth
                    continues make difficult any progress by Supomo and his comm at Hague. Subardjo
                    determined <gloss target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss> del will not be first to admit
                    impasse. He sees little prospect however of much satis progress being made by
                    Jan 15 which <gloss target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss> Govt has looked upon as
                    deadline after which policy toward negots wld have to be reviewed.</p>
                <p>Subardjo told me he is as strongly against unilateral abrogation as always. He
                    said popular <gloss target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss> resentment of Neth attitude
                    making position Sukiman Govt difficult. He said he has rapidly growing dossier
                    of evidence on Neth subversive activities East <gloss target="#t_Indo1"
                        >Indo</gloss> connected with Neth claim <gloss target="#t_NNG1">NNG</gloss>
                    and financed by group of diehards incl Gerbrandy.<note n="1" xml:id="d459fn1">P.
                        S. Gerbrandy, Netherlands Prime Minister in World War II.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cochran</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
